// Published-bare-name ambiguity oracle: a plain import must not poison a named
// opt-in of the same bare name from another module.
//
// `hew::widgetpub8` and `hew::widgetpub64` both export a public `Gadget` with a
// DIVERGENT layout (i8 vs i64). This importer opts `Gadget` in from `widgetpub8`
// only (`::{ Gadget }`) and plain-imports `widgetpub64` (which exports `Gadget`
// but does not publish it bare). A bare `Gadget` must resolve to the PUBLISHED
// owner `widgetpub8.Gadget` — not error ambiguous against the unpublished
// `widgetpub64.Gadget`, and not bind the wrong (i64) layout. The construction
// is read back through its field, so the proof turns on binding the published
// owner's i8 layout end-to-end.
//
// Ambiguity is decided over PUBLISHED bare bindings, so the plain `widgetpub64`
// import does not contribute and cannot poison the opt-in.
//
// Harness verb: hew run
// Expected: a=7 (the i8 `Gadget` from the opted-in module).
import hew::widgetpub8::{ Gadget };
import hew::widgetpub64;

fn main() {
    let a = Gadget { v: 7 };
    println(f"a={a.v}");
}
